  </head>
<body>

  <header class="header">
    <a href="#">Our Blog</a>
  </header>

  <main class="article-layout">
    <div class="article-main">
      <div class="article-header">
        <h1>Building Responsive Web Designs with CSS Grid</h1>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>By <a href="#">Jane Doe</a></span>
          <span>Published on December 2, 2023</span>
          <span>Category: <a href="#">Web Development</a></span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="article-content">
        <p>Responsive web design is no longer a luxury but a necessity. With an ever-increasing array of devices and screen sizes, ensuring your website looks and functions perfectly everywhere is paramount. CSS Grid Layout, often simply called CSS Grid, has revolutionized how developers approach layout design on the web, offering a powerful and flexible system for creating two-dimensional layouts.</p>

        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1016/800/450" alt="CSS Grid Example">

        <h2>What is CSS Grid?</h2>
        <p>CSS Grid is a two-dimensional layout system for the web. It lets you lay out elements into rows and columns, making it easy to build complex responsive designs. Unlike Flexbox, which is primarily a one-dimensional layout system (either rows or columns), Grid excels at controlling both at once, providing a robust framework for entire page layouts.</p>
        <p>Key concepts include Grid Containers, Grid Items, Grid Lines, Grid Tracks, Grid Cells, and Grid Areas. Understanding these is fundamental to mastering Grid.</p>

        <h3>Defining Your Grid</h3>
        <p>To start using CSS Grid, you declare a container element as a grid with `display: grid`. Then, you define your rows and columns using `grid-template-rows` and `grid-template-columns` properties. You can use fixed units (px), flexible units (fr), percentages, and more.</p>
        <pre><code>.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr; /* Three columns: 1 part, 2 parts, 1 part */
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto; /* Three rows: auto height, fill space, auto height */
  gap: 20px; /* Space between grid items */
}</code></pre>

        <h2>Responsive Techniques with Grid</h2>
        <p>CSS Grid makes responsive design inherently easier. Media queries can be used to redefine grid templates entirely, or you can leverage `fr` units and `grid-auto-flow: dense` for more dynamic layouts that adjust based on available space.</p>
        <p>Combining `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr))` is a particularly powerful technique. It allows you to create a grid that automatically adjusts the number of columns to fit the available space, ensuring each column is at least `250px` wide and takes up equal remaining space.</p>

        <h3>Practical Examples</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hero Sections:</strong> Easily create two-column hero sections that stack on mobile.</li>
          <li><strong>Complex Dashboards:</strong> Manage intricate arrangements of widgets and components.</li>
          <li><strong>Image Galleries:</strong> Build responsive galleries that adapt gracefully.</li>
        </ul>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1047/800/450" alt="Responsive Grid">
        <blockquote>
          "CSS Grid simplifies the complex art of web layout, allowing developers to focus more on content and less on hacks."
        </blockquote>
        <p>Embracing CSS Grid in your workflow will undoubtedly elevate your responsive design capabilities, leading to cleaner code and more maintainable layouts. It's a fundamental tool for modern web development.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

